Kotlin deals with lists in very elegant way, as you can see below. The only thing that might be not obvious is `result.map { it + num}` which for each list in result adds current element `num`. BUT `map` doesn't modify collection itself (`result` in this case), it returns mapped lists.
```
    fun subsets(nums: IntArray): List<List<Int>> {
        val result = mutableListOf(emptyList<Int>())
        nums.forEach { num ->
            val newAdditions = result.map { it + num}
            result.addAll(newAdditions)
        }
        return result
    }

