The problem can be solved using binary search, an efficient algorithm to find an element in a sorted array. In this case, we have a range of versions from 1 to n, and we need to find the first bad version. The versions are sorted in ascending order, and we want to minimize the number of checks (API calls) to determine whether a version is bad or not.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
The binary search algorithm has a time complexity of O(log n), which is very efficient compared to a linear search that would have O(n) time complexity.

- Space complexity:
The space complexity of this approach is O(1), as we only use a constant amount of extra space for the pointers low and high.

# Code
```
// The API isBadVersion is defined for you.
// bool isBadVersion(int version);

class Solution {
public:
    int firstBadVersion(int n) {
        if(n==1)
        return n;

        int low=1,high=n;
        while(low<high)
        {
            int mid=low+(high-low)/2;
            if(isBadVersion(mid))
            high=mid;
            else
            low=mid+1;

        }
        return low;

    }
};
```

