# Intuition using Priority queue
We are maintaining a max heap of size k. whenever it is exceeding size k we are polling the top element which is the max element.this way in the end we will be left with only k elements and and we will return it will give us the max of all k elements which is the kth largest.

# Approach 1 using Priority queue (Not preferred)
In this approach we will use a maxHeap of size k. The algorithm is as follows:
1. Traverse over all the elements in O(n^2) time and add it to the priority queue. if the size of the max heap exceeds k. poll the element from the maxHeap.
2. return the top element of the maxheap once the traversal is done.

<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n^2log(k))
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n) (max value of k can be n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


```
class Solution {
    // TC : O(n^2logk)
    public int kthSmallest(int[][] matrix, int k) {
        int n = matrix.length+matrix[0].length;
        PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<Integer>(Collections.reverseOrder());
        for(int i=0;i<matrix.length;i++)
            for(int j=0;j<matrix[0].length;j++)
            {

                pq.add(matrix[i][j]);
                if(pq.size()>k)
                    pq.poll();

            }
            return pq.poll();
    }
}
```
# Intuition 2 using binary search and optimized counting
We know that the kth largest number will lie somewhere in between the top left element and bottom right element. we will take the two numbers.
we can omit a large portion of the array each time using the binary search. 

# Approach 2 using binary search and optimized counting
In this approach we will take the smallest and biggest element of the matrix and perform binary search each time with some some special operation other than just searching.
we will count the number of elements smaller than or equal to mid each time instead of just equating in normal binary search.
**The algorithm for binary search is as follows:**
1. take the smallest element of matrix as low and highest as high.
2. find the mid of the low and high and count the number of elements smaller then or equal to it in the matrix using the optimized counting approach in 
O(n+n) time.
    ****if(the count of smaller elements is greater than or equal to k):****
        then we need to shorten out search and move towards left side on the range:: high =mid-1

    ****else:****
        shorten the search and move to right part :: low=mid+1 

ONE OBVIOUS QUESTION:
if we get count of smaller or equal element   in matrix equal to k then why dont we stop.
Beacuse we wan to find the value which exists in the matrix.

****we are considering the range between the smallest and the highest element in the matrix. ****


**The algorithm for optimized counting of elements in matrix smaller than or equal to mid is as follows:**
We know that the matrix is sorted in row wise and column wise. 
hence,
1. all the elements to the bottom of an element is bigger than the element 
2.  all the elements to the right of the array will also be bigger than the element
we will use this concept to get the count number of smaller and equal to elements in the matrix in O(n+n)time.

The algorithm is as follows :
1. start from the top right element of the matrix.
    if (it is smaller than mid): 
    {
        then move to next row(r++);
        count all the elements of the row skipped(count =count+c+1) [0 based index hence add 1]
    }   
    else:
    {
        move to left unless an element less than k is found(
            while(c>=0 && matrix[r][c]>mid)
                c--;
        )
        count all the elements (count=count+c+1;)
        move to the next row; (r++)
    }

