# Intuition
Using **Min Heap** - *in Min Heap, for every node, the value of node is lesser than it's child nodes. And the ROOT is the smallest value in the Heap.* 
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
- *Store the entire matrix into a Min Heap.* 
- The **Topmost element** of the heap is the **smallest element** of the array.
- So, ***if we delete K-1 elements from the heap, then the element at the top will be the Kth Smallest Element.*** 
- Iterate till **K is greater than one** *(Take K or take a counter variable equal to 1 & iterate till it is not equal to K)*
    - In each iteration 
        - *Pop from the heap.*
        - *Decrease value of K by one.*
- The element at the **top of the heap is Kth smallest element**
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:$$O(N)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:$$O(N)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```C++ []
class Solution {
public:
    int kthSmallest(vector<vector<int>>& matrix, int k) {

        priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int> > minHeap ; 

        int row = matrix.size() ; 
        int col = matrix[0].size() ;

        for (int i = 0 ; i < row ; i ++)
        {
            for (int j = 0 ; j < col ; j ++)
            {
                minHeap.push(matrix[i][j]) ;
            }
        }

        while (k > 1)
        {
            minHeap.pop() ; 
            k -- ; 
        }

        return minHeap.top() ; 
    }
};
```
