# Intuition
Using **Max Heap** - *in Max Heap, for every node, the value of node is greater than it's child nodes. And the ROOT is the largest value in the Heap.* 
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
- *Store the entire matrix into a Max Heap.* 
- The **Topmost element** of the heap is the **greatest element** of the array.
- So, ***if we reduce the size of the maxHeap priority queue to K elements*** 
- Iterate till **Size of Max Heap is greater than K** 
    - In each iteration 
        - *Pop from the heap.*
- Now, *the size of our Heap is equal to K and only the K smallest elements are stored in it*
- The **Kth smallest element is the largest element out of these K elements and is stored at the top.**
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:$$O(N)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:$$O(N)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```C++ []
class Solution {
public:
    int kthSmallest(vector<vector<int>>& matrix, int k) {

        priority_queue<int> maxHeap ; 

        int row = matrix.size() ; 
        int col = matrix[0].size() ;

        for (int i = 0 ; i < row ; i ++)
        {
            for (int j = 0 ; j < col ; j ++)
            {
                maxHeap.push(matrix[i][j]) ;
            }
        }

        while (maxHeap.size() > k)
        {
            maxHeap.pop() ; 
        }

        return maxHeap.top() ; 
    }
};

