This is a C++ code that aims to find the kth smallest element in a 2D matrix by using a priority queue data structure.

The code first creates an empty max heap using the priority_queue container with the default comparator (which is std::less). Then, it loops through each element in the matrix and inserts them into the max heap.

If the size of the max heap exceeds k, it removes the top element (which is the maximum element in the heap). Since we want to find the kth smallest element, we only keep the k smallest elements in the max heap.

Finally, the function returns the top element of the max heap, which is the kth smallest element in the matrix.

Therefore, the code has a time complexity of O(N log k), where N is the total number of elements in the matrix, and k is the input parameter indicating the kth smallest element to be found.





