solutions.content:
Approach:
In the matrix, we know that the smallest and largest elements are (the upperleft and the lowerright respectively).
Let `lowerBound` and `upperBound` be the smallest and largest element respectively. All elements in the matrix will lie in the range `[lowerBound, upperBound]`.

We then find the `mid` value of them (the average value) and then find the number of elements in the matrix that are smaller or equal to `mid`. Let's call that number `rank`.

If `rank` < k, we know that the wanted element must be larger than `mid` so we search to the right of `mid` (thus `lowerBound = mid + 1`).
Otherwise, we know that the wanted element must be on the left of `mid` or `mid` itself, therefore we limit the search range from `[lowerBound, mid]`.

We keep doing that until the search range only has 1 item left.

Code:
```
class Solution {
    public int kthSmallest(int[][] matrix, int k) {
        int cols = matrix[0].length;
        int rows = matrix.length;

        // The upper left element will be the smallest item
        int lowerBound = matrix[0][0];
        // The lower right element will be the larget item
        // Together with the lowerBound, we have to largest range in the matrix
        int upperBound = matrix[rows - 1][cols - 1];

        while (lowerBound < upperBound) {
            int mid = (lowerBound + upperBound) / 2;
            int rank = rank(matrix, mid);

            // If there are at least k elements in the matrix
            // that are smaller than mid, we need to reduce the range to the left
            if (rank >= k)
                upperBound = mid;

            // Other wise we search to the right to get a larger rank
            else
                lowerBound = mid + 1;
        }

        return lowerBound;
    }

    /* Find the total number of items in the matrix that are less than or equal to the target */
    private int rank(int[][] matrix, int target) {
        int rows = matrix.length;
        int cols = matrix[0].length;

        int row = rows - 1;
        int col = 0;

        int count = 0;
        // Start from the bottom left element where we have the largest item
        // of the first column and the smallest item in the last row
        while (row >= 0 && col < cols) {

            // If the current item is less than the target
            // we move to the right to test the larger element
            // and we know that all elements in that same column
            // will also smaller than target, so we add them all to count and don't
            // go back to that column again

            if (matrix[row][col] <= target) {
                col++;
                count = count + (row + 1);
            }

            // If the current item is larger than target
            // we know that all items to the right on the same row
            // will be also larger than target, so we don't search that row anymore
            // but instead move to the upper row

            else {
                row--;
            }
        }

        return count;
    }
}
```

