solutions.content:
I fell into the same trap as a lot of people, using polar coordinates without normalizing with square root. I figured it out when I plotted my results in excel, and saw that areas farther from the center were a lot more sparse.

However, I didn't come up with the clever (and probably more "correct") solution of normalizing with square root. Instead, I used the coveted "spray and pray" approach.

The gist of my approach is as follows:

Imagine the smallest square that completely encloses the circle (call it the "fool's square"). Its lower left corner will be at coordinates `(x - radius, y - radius)`. If we find this lower left corner, and generate a random (x,y) coordinate pair within this square, it will have an even distribution within the circle. We can implement this approach directly **except** for the case when the random coordinate point happens to fall "out of bounds" (i.e. in one of the four areas between the square and circle at each of the square's corners. In these cases, we just discard the value and retry until we get a valid in-bounds value.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/0722ebca-47ca-439f-bf73-95c460a72276_1615991913.8184464.jpeg)

This is not the prettiest solution, and I am sure an interviewer would prefer to see the square root method. But for us mere mortals, this is a decent hack. Code below.

```
class Solution {
    double r, x, y;
    Random rand;
    public Solution(double radius, double x_center, double y_center) {
        this.rand = new Random();
        this.r = radius;
        this.x = x_center;
        this.y = y_center;
    }

    public double[] randPoint() {
        // x0, y0 is the "origin"; imagine a square tangent to the circle
        // on the top/bottom/left/right; (x0, y0) is the coordinate of its lower left corner
        double x0 = x-r, y0 = y-r;

        // generate a random value somewhere in the fool's square
        double dx = 2*r*rand.nextDouble();
        double dy = 2*r*rand.nextDouble();

        // user pythagorean theorem (a^2 + b^2 = c^2) to figure out if the point
        // is actually within the circle, or "out of bounds"
        double a2 = Math.pow(Math.abs(x0+dx-x), 2);
        double b2 = Math.pow(Math.abs(y0+dy-y), 2);
        double c2 = Math.pow(r, 2);
        if(a2+b2 <= c2) {
	    // point is in bounds; return it
            return new double[]{x0+dx, y0+dy};
        } else {
	    // point is out of bounds; retry
            return randPoint();   
        } 
    }
}
```

