solutions.content:
Let's start from a formalization of the problem description.

## Definition

How do we define *a uniform distribution of points in the circle*? 

Consider points in an area as an infinite (and uncountable) set - and the area represents the *measure* of the set. This is so-called [Lebesgue measure](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebesgue_measure) of a 2-dimensional Euclidean space.

The probability of selecting a measurable subset should be given by a probability measure with the whole circle assigned total measure 1. Thus the probability measure of *uniform distribution* can be defined as proportion of the area (Lebesgue measure) of measurable subset to the whole circle.

## Proof

Since we have established the relationship between probability and area, we only need to find construct a probability distribution whose CDF is equal to the proportion of area.

For convenience, we transform the Cartesian coordinates to polar coordinates. Recall how we do [surface integral for polar coordinates](https://www.math.ucla.edu/~archristian/teaching/32b-sum18/session-2.pdf). The integrand is the reciprocal of the area of circle.

Compare it with the [joint PDF](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_density_function#Independence) of two indenpendent random variables. The only difference is `r`, so we only need to construct a distribution with linear PDF from a uniform distribution. This is why we apply square root to a uniformly distributed random variable.

## Solution

### Closed Range

Notice that most random libraries provide a half-closed range. This problem states explicitly that 
> 3. a point on the circumference of the circle is considered to be in the circle.

Most posts made a mistake - they didn't take the upper bound (points on the circumference) into account, because it's exclusive for most standard libraries in programming languages.

Let's take a look at Java's [official doc](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/15/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Math.html#random()) on `Math.random()`:
> As the largest double value less than 1.0 is Math.nextDown(1.0), a value x in the closed range [x1,x2] where x1<=x2 may be defined by the statements
> ```
>  double f = Math.random()/Math.nextDown(1.0);
>  double x = x1*(1.0 - f) + x2*f;
> ```

### Independent Random Variable

Another mistake made by most posts is that pseudorandom numbers are generated from the same sequence when using the same seed.

If both of the Cartesian or polar coordinates are generated using the same seed, they're **NOT** independent random variables any more, which breaks the premise to derive joint PDF.

Therefore we should maintain two *independent* random variables with different seeds instead sharing one (like `Math.random()`).

### Another Approach: Rejection Sampling

Related problem:
- [470. Implement Rand10() Using Rand7()](https://leetcode.com/problems/implement-rand10-using-rand7/)

This problem showed us how to construct a uniformly distributed discrete random variable using another with a larger event space. For continuous case, that applies too. Imagine we're randomly pitching a coin into a square which exactly encompasses the circle, and repeat until the coin falls into the circle.

This is the initial solution I thought of and it's more generalizable. With an average time complexity of O(4/π), however, the worst case suffers an infinite time cost.

### Implementation

#### Polar Coordinates

```java
class Solution {
    private double xCenter;
    private double yCenter;
    private double radius;

    private Random rhRandom;
    private Random thRandom;

    public Solution(double radius, double xCenter, double yCenter) {
        this.radius = radius;
        this.xCenter = xCenter;
        this.yCenter = yCenter;

        rhRandom = new Random();
        thRandom = new Random();
    }

    public double[] randPoint() {
        if (radius <= 0) return new double[0];

        double rho = radius * Math.sqrt(rhRandom.nextDouble() / Math.nextDown(1.0));
        double theta = 2 * Math.PI * thRandom.nextDouble();

        double x = xCenter + rho * Math.cos(theta);
        double y = yCenter + rho * Math.sin(theta);

        return new double[]{x, y};
    }
}

/**
 * Your Solution object will be instantiated and called as such:
 * Solution obj = new Solution(radius, x_center, y_center);
 * double[] param_1 = obj.randPoint();
 */
 ```


#### Rejection Sampling

```java
class Solution {
    private double xCenter;
    private double yCenter;
    private double radius;

    private Random xRandom;
    private Random yRandom;

    public Solution(double radius, double xCenter, double yCenter) {
        this.radius = radius;
        this.xCenter = xCenter;
        this.yCenter = yCenter;

        xRandom = new Random();
        yRandom = new Random();
    }

    public double[] randPoint() {
        if (radius <= 0) return new double[0];

        double xLower = xCenter - radius;
        double xUpper = xCenter + radius;
        double yLower = yCenter - radius;
        double yUpper = yCenter + radius;

        double[] res = new double[2];

        do {
            res[0] = generateRandom(xLower, xUpper, xRandom);
            res[1] = generateRandom(yLower, yUpper, yRandom);
        } while (!inCircle(res[0], res[1]));

        return res;
    }

    private boolean inCircle(double x, double y) {
        double dist = Math.sqrt(Math.pow(x - xCenter, 2) + Math.pow(y - yCenter, 2));
        return dist <= radius;
    }

    // lower - inclusive, upper - inclusive
    private double generateRandom(double lower, double upper, Random random) {
        // Generate [0.0, 1.0] uniformly distributed
        double rand = random.nextDouble() / Math.nextDown(1.0);
        return lower * (1 - rand) + upper * rand;
    }
}

/**
 * Your Solution object will be instantiated and called as such:
 * Solution obj = new Solution(radius, x_center, y_center);
 * double[] param_1 = obj.randPoint();
 */
