# Intuition
Polar coordinates of a circle is:

x = x_origin + r * cos(theta)
y = y_origin + r * sin(theta)

where r is the radius and theta is the angle made when joining the point (x,y) to the center of the cirecle, i.e., (x_origin, y_origin). 

So, if we randomize the r and theta to take random values within the circle area, we will get the correct solution for this problem.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(1)

- Space complexity: O(1)

# Code
```
#include <math.h>
class Solution {
private: 
    double rad, x_cen, y_cen;
public:
    Solution(double radius, double x_center, double y_center) {
        rad = radius;
        x_cen = x_center;
        y_cen = y_center;
    }

    vector<double> randPoint() {
        double r = sqrt((double)rand()/RAND_MAX)*rad;
        double deg = ((double)rand()/RAND_MAX)*2*M_PI;
        vector<double> cord(2,0);
        cord[0] = x_cen+(r*cos(deg));
        cord[1] = y_cen+(r*sin(deg));
        return cord;
    }
};

/**
 * Your Solution object will be instantiated and called as such:
 * Solution* obj = new Solution(radius, x_center, y_center);
 * vector<double> param_1 = obj->randPoint();
 */


